!TITLE
JONATHAN EDWARDS' ZEAL
!WORDS
The Lord has promised to bless the efforts of those who serve Him 
with warm devotion and true zeal.  Jonathan Edwards, a preacher in 
colonial New England, was a shining example of a man with these 
qualities.  Although his voice and pulpit manner were not commanding, 
many of his sermons had an overwhelming impact upon the people who 
heard him.  His message "Sinners in the Hands of an Angry God" moved 
hundreds to repentance and salvation.  In fact, according to 
historians, that one address helped spark a revival known as "The 
Great Awakening."

   From a human standpoint it is hard to account for such 
far-reaching results from a single discourse.  The speaker was not 
dynamic, nor did he use many gestures; yet he spoke with deep 
sincerity.  Few knew the spiritual preparation involved in that 
sermon.  John Chapman gives us the story: "For 3 days Edwards had not 
eaten a mouthful of food; for 3 nights he had not closed his eyes in 
sleep.  Over and over again he was heard to pray, 'O Lord, give me 
New England!  Give me New England!'  When he arose from his knees and 
made his way into the pulpit that Sunday, he looked as if he had been 
gazing straight into the face of God.  Even before he began to speak, 
tremendous conviction fell upon his audience."
!TOPICS
PREACHING, POWER OF
SENSITIVITY TO GOD
PRAYER FOR POWER
REVIVAL THROUGH PRAYER
GREAT AWAKENING
EDWARDS, JONATHAN
