!TITLE
LEARNING THROUGH SUFFERING
!WORDS
C. H. Spurgeon understood the need for suffering, for he wrote, 
"Stars may be seen from the bottom of a deep well that cannot be 
discerned from the top of a mountain: so are many things learned in 
adversity which the prosperous man dreams not of. We need affliction 
as the trees need winter, that we may collect sap and nourishment for 
future blossoms and fruit.  Sorrow is as necessary for the soul as 
medicine is to the body.
    'The path of sorrow, and that path alone,
     Leads to the land where sorrow is unknown.'"
!TOPICS
