!TITLE
WORRY--FEAR'S EXTRAVAGANCE
!WORDS
An unknown poet has written:

    "I heard a voice at evening softly say,
      'Bear not thy yesterdays into tomorrow,
   Nor load this week
      With last week's load of sorrow.
    Lift all thy burdens as they come,
      Nor try to weigh
    The present with the by-and-by.
      One step and then another

    Take thy way--live day by day!'" Doctors point out that such 
constant apprehension is also physically harmful because brooding 
over troubles- -real or imagined--may result in the added problems of 
stomach ulcers, high blood pressure, and nervous tension.
