!TITLE
WAITING TO DIE
!WORDS
Scientific evidence supports a unique phenomenon observed time after 
time by doctors and chaplains who counsel the dying.  It shows that 
people often delay death by the determination of their own will until 
after some significant event has occurred. One study, for instance, 
revealed that 46 percent of a random sampling of people died in the 
first 3 months after their birthday, and only 8 percent died in the 3 
months immediately preceding the same milestone.  Additional research 
indicates an unexplainable decrease in deaths before presidential 
elections and, with large Jewish populations, before Yom Kippur, the 
day of atonement.

    These interesting facts remind us that Jesus resisted death until 
a special day-the feast of Passover.  He didn't let men take His life 
before that significant event.  Although He was hated during His 
public ministry and His enemies plotted to kill Him, He carefully 
avoided being caught in their evil designs. Humanly speaking, it 
would have been easier for Him to have given up earlier so that He 
could escape the naked humiliation of the cross.  Yet He waited.  
Because He was obedient to the Father, He willed to live until His 
"hour" had come to die.
!TOPICS
DEATH, TIMING OF
COUNSEL, TO THE DYING
BIRTHDAY, SIGNIFICANCE OF
!SCRIPTURES
JOHN 8:19-30
JOHN 10:18
!BASE=ILLY/1
!SOURCE=0
!MSTATUS=16385
!TCAID=2544
!QSID=19864
!END


!TITLE
SEEING JESUS IN THE MORNING
!WORDS
Under the Old Testament law, the Levites were required to arise and 
"stand every morning to thank and praise the Lord, and likewise at 
evening" (1 Chr. 23:30).  According to the New Testament, all 
believers are priests (1 Pet. 2:5,9), and the Lord expects them to 
commune with Him daily.  And those who begin the day with God are 
most likely to sense His presence in all that they do.

    A little 4-year-old boy said to his parents one morning, "I won't 
get up until I see Jesus."  At first they didn't know what he meant, 
but then the little fellow pointed to a picture on the wall.  It was 
a painting of Christ.  He wouldn't get out of bed until it was light 
enough to see the face of Jesus.  They learned an important spiritual 
lesson from their son's innocent remark.  It taught them never to 
begin their day's work until they had first "seen Jesus" in a time of 
meditation and prayer.
     We should get our souls in tune with God before the concert of 
the day begins.
!TOPICS
DEVOTION, TO GOD
MORNING, TIME FOR WORSHIP
LEVITES, WORSHIPING GOD
WORSHIP
