!TITLE
LOW-INTENSITY FIRE
!WORDS
On June 26, 1977, a bolt of lightning started a fire in California's 
Kings Canyon National Park. A month later the flames had spread over 
3,000 acres of land, and no attempt had been made to put them out.  
Nothing was done because the National Park Service believes that some 
low-intensity fires are essential to the maintenance of our forest 
lands. They've discovered that since the late 1800s, when fire 
suppression policies were introduced, our national forest have begun 
to clutter up. Dead materials and thickets of young shade-tolerant 
trees have accumulated to the point that any fire could become a 
raging holocaust. Consequently, the Park Service is attempting, 
through research and careful management, the controlled burning of 
certain plots.  With the dead wood reduced, fires occurring from 
lightning will once again be allowed to play their natural role.  The 
forest undergrowth will then be cleared, the hard- shelled seed coats 
of fire-dependent species will be broken, and new seedbeds prepared.

  The life of a Christian also needs periodic purging.  In the 
shadows of our victories are scrubby little loves and distractions 
that can sap our life and strength.  If we willfully smother the 
advice, constructive criticism, or teaching that God brings into our 
lives, selfish habits will accumulate to our own hurt.
!TOPICS
TRIALS
SUFFERING, PURPOSE IN
CREATION, GOD'S WONDERFUL
CREATOR, GOD OUR
DESIGN, IN CREATION
