!TITLE
RENEWED HOPE
!WORDS
One woman told of reaching a point of despair in her role as a 
pastor's wife.  She cited some of the stresses she faced: sharing her 
husband 24 hours a day, resenting perfectionist standards, feeling 
guilty about recurring bitterness and anger, and having no one to 
share her feelings with.  Gradually she became so discouraged that 
she was ready to give up.

  One day she opened her sorely neglected Bible to the writings of 
the prophet Jeremiah.  As she read, she felt as if she were watching 
over Jeremiah's shoulder as the potter worked a lump of clay on his 
wheel.  She began to get emotionally involved when the clay became 
marred in the potter's hand.  Between the lines she assumed the 
potter would toss aside the lump of spoiled clay to take up another, 
hoping for better results. For a moment her life was that lump of 
clay, and she felt the old nagging fear that God, like this potter, 
might lay aside her disappointing life and take up another to do His 
work.  But she read on to see what the potter really did with the 
clay: 'and he reworked it into another vessel, as it seemed good for 
the potter to do!' As if written for her alone, the next verse read, 
"Can I not do with you as this potter has done? says the Lord. 
Behold, like the clay in the potter's hand, so are you in My hand.'"  
With renewed hope, the pastor's wife realized that God was molding 
her for His use.
!TOPICS
DISCOURAGEMENT
HOPE
USEFULNESS
JEREMIAH
RENEWAL
