!TITLE
USELESS WORRY
!WORDS
Worry has been defined as "a small trickle of fear that meanders 
through the mind until it cuts a channel into which all other 
thoughts are drained."  The psalmist told of the futility of rising 
up early and sitting up late to mull over troubles that are beyond 
control (Psalm 127:2). Ian Maclaren warned against the adverse 
effects of worry.  "What does your anixety do?" he asked. "It does 
not empty tomorrow of its sorrow, but is does empty today of its 
strength.  It does not make you escape the evil; it makes you unfit 
to cope with it when it comes."

  J. Arthur Rank devised a practical way of handling this problem.  
Not having enough faith to overcome his troubles immediately, he 
decided that the next best thing was to postpone thinking about them 
until his mind had cleared.  So when something disturbing occured, he 
wrote the problem on a card and would not dwell on it until a little 
time had passed.  Then when he reviewed the difficulties that had  
been of such concern a week or so before, he found to his surprise 
that most of them had already disappeared.  He therefore concluded 
that much of his distress was a waste of energy and loss of sleep, 
for God had intervened and directed his life in ways he had never 
envisioned.
!TOPICS
WORRY
ANXIETY
AFFLICTION
TROUBLE
FAITH
!SCRIPTURES
PSALMS 127:2
MATTHEW 10:16-42
MATTHEW 6:25-34
PHILIPPIANS 4:6
1 PETER 5:7
PSALMS 55:22
