!TITLE
YES MEN BECOME NOBODIES
!WORDS
Yes is a little word that can often spell big trouble.  A seminary 
president once said, "Always saying 'yes' causes one to lose his 
identity, whereas 'no' defines a person."

  Suppose some morning you decide to say yes to every request that 
comes to you that day.  You say yes to every demand placed on your 
time, talents, and energies.  You say yes regardless of your 
convictions.  What condition would you be in by the end of the day?  
You'd feel as if you'd been pulled in all directions-- not to mention 
your guilt and loss of self-respect for not saying no to what was 
wrong.

  Moses defined himself by refusing "to be called the son of 
Pharaoh's daughter."  We as Christians must also learn to say no to 
many things.  This doesn't mean we become negative or disagreeable. 
On the contrary, every no should be the reverse side of a hearty yes 
to God.  The Bible lists many things that are wrong (see Galatians 
5:19-21). And for those things that are neither right nor wrong in 
themselves, discernment comes through prayer, trusting in God's 
Spirit, and applying biblical principles.
!TOPICS
CONVICTIONS
DISCERNMENT
NEGATIVISM
IDENTITY
COMMITMENT
!SCRIPTURES
GALATIANS 5:19-21
TITUS 2:12
MATTHEW 16:24
ROMANS 6:12
1 CORINTHIANS 6:12
1 CORINTHIANS 10:23
2 CORINTHIANS 1:20
!BASE=ILLY/1
!SOURCE=0
!MSTATUS=16385
!TCAID=3587
!QSID=19901
!END


!TITLE
OUR TRUSTWORTHY FRIEND
!WORDS
Not too many years ago, a Christian writer went through a deep period 
of doubt and temptation.  He questioned his ministry, his 
qualifications, his marriage, his salvation.  Anguished and burdened, 
he finally went to a friend and confessed his feelings.  As they 
talked and prayed together over the course of several weeks, his 
perspective returned.  Peace came to his heart, and he experienced 
the joy of the Lord again.

  If we can receive such help from talking with a friend, how much 
more beneficial would it be to be completely open with God? He is the 
best of friends.  Alexander Maclaren wrote, "If we are friends of 
God, we shall have no secrets from Him. There are very few of those 
who are dearest to us to whom we would venture to lay bare all the 
depths of our hearts.  There are things down in the cellars that we 
do not like to show to any of our friends....But you should let God 
all through the house.  If there is trust and love, we shall not be 
afraid to spread out all our foulness, and our meanness, and our 
unworthy thoughts and acts towards Him.  Tell God all, if you mean to 
be a friend of His."
!TOPICS
FRIENDSHIP WITH GOD
CONFESSION
SECRETS
PRAYER
OPENNESS
HONESTY
TRUST
CHRISTIAN LIFE
!SCRIPTURES
JAMES 2:23
