!TITLE
FACING YOUR PAST
!WORDS
Our past has a way of tracking us throughout life. Several years ago 
when Dennis De Haan spoke in a church in Cortland, New York, one of 
the deacons told him he had recently met De Haan's high school 
football coach.  The man from Cortland had mentioned that a speaker 
from Michigan by the name of Dennis De Haan was coming to his church. 
Immediately a light flashed in the other man's mind.  Someone by that 
name played football when he coached in Zeeland, Michigan.  So after 
25 years, a little bit of De Haan's former life surfaced in the 
present.  He wondered if the coach might also have recalled some of 
his mistakes on the gridiron?

  Being reminded of a few football errors is harmless enough, but 
being haunted by sins we wish to forget can be disturbing. They can 
crop up long after we think they've been forgotten.  To be free from 
the specter of a shameful past, we must face up to it.  Writing to 
Timothy, Paul spoke of his own sinful conduct before he had become a 
Christian.   He neither justified it nor denied it, but admitted it.  
Yet he wasn't harassed by it, because Christ had stricken it from the 
record and had given him a new life.  His past was truly a thing of 
the past.
!TOPICS
SPIRITUAL GROWTH
SINS, PAST
FORGIVENESS
!SCRIPTURES
PHILIPPIANS 3:13
PSALMS 25:7
ECCLESIASTES 11:9
1 TIMOTHY 1:13
