!TITLE
NO INSTANT MATURITY
!WORDS
In all areas of life, maturity takes time.
  A student asked his college president if he could take a shorter 
course than the one required. "Oh, yes," answered the president, "but 
then it depends on what you want to be.  When God wants to make an 
oak, He takes a hundred years.  When He makes a squash, He takes 6 
months."

  The period of rapid growth in a tree, the time when woody fiber is 
deposited, requires only 4 to 6 weeks.  But the continued nourishment 
of the tree, the hardening and strengthening of the fiber, takes not 
months but years.  The same applies to Christian maturity.  Like the 
college student, we might desire a "short course" and say, "Please, 
Lord, let me skip the trials; hurry up the process so I can arrive at 
maturity."  But there are no shortcuts to spirtual maturity.
!TOPICS
