!TITLE
HOW CAN THEY SEE GOD
!WORDS
In 1986, Soviet firemen and other rescue workers gave their lives to 
put out the nuclear fire at Chernobyl.  In recognition of their 
sacrifice, the Russian newspaper Pravda published this poem:

  God is in a man who walked into a radiated complex,
  Put out the fire, burned his skin and clothes,
  Who didn't save himself,
  But saved Odessa and Kiev,
  A man who simply acted like a human being.

  An American bone transplant specialist, Dr. Robert Gale, also 
assisted the Soviets.  As evidence of their gratitude, the poem went 
on to say that god was also in Dr. Gale.

  Russia, of course, is atheistic, and many of her people do not 
believe in God, yet Pravda's use of the term "god" is significant.  
It reminds us of the kind of impact the apostle Paul wanted his life 
to have.  His deep desire was that others would see in his life so 
much love and self-sacrifice that they would find it natural to give 
credit to God.  He believed that people observing him as he faced 
danger and endured persecution would see the glory of Christ's 
presence in his life.
!TOPICS
SELF-SACRIFICE
GRATITUDE
GLORY, GOD'S
ATHEISM
REVELATION
USSR
CHERNOBYL
