!TITLE
MONOTONE BUT NOT MONOTONOUS
!WORDS
The famous Italian composer Rossini was asked to write an opera for a 
musical group.  There was one problem:  the person who sang contralto 
in the group could sing well on only one note(middle B-flat).  It was 
a bizarre request, but the composer simply accepted this limitation 
and wrote a beautiful aria, creating harmonies for the orchestra and 
chorus.

    "Some of us have only 'one good note' to play with on our best 
day!  But God can take that one note--if we're open and willing to be 
led--and create a brilliant masterpiece out of our lives with it."
 From "Giant-killing 101" by Jeris Bragan. Discipleship Journal, 
Sep/Oct 1990. Page 10.
