!TITLE
REPENT AND BELIEVE!
!WORDS
Ben Oliphint says word meanings are so important. By analyzing the 
meaning of a single word, Martin Luther managed to transform the 
religious thought of his day.  For hundreds of years the word 
"repent" had been construed to mean "do penance and feel miserable 
about it."  Young Luther certainly did more than his share of penance 
and felt more miserable about it than almost anyone. Said Luther: "I 
kept the rules of penance so strictly that I many say that if ever a 
monk got to heaven by his sheer monkery, it was I.  Had I kept on any 
longer, I should have killed myself with vigils, prayers, readings, 
and other works."

   Luther's astounding discovery was that "repent" did not really 
mean to do penance but rather, as the Greek METANOIA indicates, to 
change your mind, to think again or in a new way, to look at 
everything differently.  He noted also that when Jesus used the word, 
it was always linked with belief:  repent and believe.  Repenting and 
believing, however, are not two distinct steps to take, one after the 
other.  They are two aspects of a single process.  To repent is, in 
effect, to believe.

  "Illustrations for Preaching" by Clyde Chesnutt. Clergy Journal, 
Feb 1991.  Page 39.
!TOPICS
