!TITLE
THE OWL THAT WINKED
!WORDS
One of the most destructive practices among Christians is that of 
being unnecessarily critical.  We set ourselves up as judges of our 
fellow believers, making unjust and harmful comments either to their 
faces or behind their backs.  Too often we are like the person in the 
anonymous poem who said of himself:
                Faults in others I can see;
                But praise the Lord,
                There's none in me. 

Once a young man's habit of criticizing backfired on him.  One 
evening, while waiting for bus, he was standing with a crowd of 
people looking in the window of a taxidermist shop.  In the center of 
the window was a large owl that attracted the attention of all who 
passed by.  The self-appointed expert began to criticize the job done 
on it.   "If I couldn't do better than that," he said pompously, "I'd 
find another business.  Just look at it.  The head is out of 
proportion, the pose of the body is unnatural, and the feet are 
pointed in the wrong direction." Just then the owl turned his head 
and gave the fellow a broad wink.  The crowd laughed as the critic 
slinked away.
!TOPICS
CRITICAL SPIRIT
JUDGMENTAL ATTITUDE
KNOW-IT-ALLS
HUMILIATION
BLIND SPOTS
