!TITLE
THE GOOD LIFE
!WORDS
 A minister who had not been feeling well went to see his doctor.  
After a thorough examination, he was given the shocking news that he 
had a terminal illness.  He was told, however, that the time of his 
death would be affected to a large degree by his workload.  The 
doctor therefore suggested that he resign his position and take it 
easy, avoiding the pressures that would shorten his life.  The 
minister asked, "How long will I live if I do as you recommend?"  
About 6 years," the doctor answered.  The minister went on, "How long 
will I live if I continue to work?"  No more than 3 years," came the 
answer.  The pastor thought for a moment, then said with conviction, 
"Doctor, I prefer living 2 or 3 years in doing some good to living 6 
years in idleness."

  Now, there is nothing wrong with slowing down if necessary, and we 
should take care of our bodies. But whether we are young or old, we 
should determine to make our lives count for Christ.  Of greater 
importance than the span of our lives is the quality of our lives.  
So, let's avoid foolish idleness and be busy serving the Lord.
!TOPICS
SERVICE TO GOD
IDLENESS
STRESS
DILIGENCE
COMMITMENT
HEALTH
PURPOSE IN LIFE
MINISTRY
DEATH
