!TITLE
TETHERED BY ADVERSITY
!WORDS
  A gentleman in England was visiting a friend who had a stable of 
famous riding horses.  He noticed that one of the beautiful animals 
feeding in the pasture had a weight fastened to its leg, which 
hindered its free motion.  "Why did you put a clog on that fine 
horse?" he asked.  His friend replied, "I'd much rather do that than 
let him run free.  He has a tendency to leap over fences and hedges 
and could permanently injure himself if he wasn't controlled."  The 
owner was using good judgment, even though the animal didn't like 
being restrained.  So too, God sometimes needs to put a "tether" on 
our lives to prevent us from unwise actions.

  J. B. Nicholson makes this helpful comment, "Many a tried and 
perplexed child of God has cried out, 'What good can ever come out of 
this?'  Well, the good of Romans 8:28 is answered in part by the 
glory of verse 29, which tells us that by these things we are being 
conformed to the image of God's Son.  Someday the Lord will finish 
the work He has already begun here through those restraining 
circumstances and the discipline of His perfect will."
!TOPICS
