!TITLE
LIFE AMIDST DEATH
!WORDS
 A man in Australia wrote to a ministry in the United States:

    "I have recently moved onto 38 acres of ex- sheep country which I 
think to farm.  We are in the middle of a fairly severe drought; the 
grass is brown and dead, the sheep that remain are thin and gaunt, 
and three horses on the property are eating the bark off trees to 
stay alive!  There is no water on my land and none anywhere else, for 
that matter. Everyone is complaining about 'how bad things are.'  But 
it has taught me a lesson.
    "Over the last three weeks there has been light patchy rain, 
about 3/4-inch or so.  Not that there is any visible improvement--or 
is there?  I noticed a few days ago that there are small clumps of 
grass, quite vivid green (against the parched brown paddock), very 
'fragile,' only a foot or so across, quite hard to see from a 
distance because the little blades of grass are but 1/4-inch long! 
There are signs of life in the 'death' I am sitting amidst!
    "The world is just like my property and this drought.  The 
general appearance is uniformity and death.  But there are tiny 
little clumps of life. Jesus said to the disciples that the fields 
were'white unto harvest'--down here... I've certainly now seen that 
the life of my land, like the 'life' in the world, is something that 
needs to be carefully sought and tenderly nurtured."
   [CIB Bulletin, Jun 1992. Page 4.]
!TOPICS
LIFE, NEW
DROUGHT
DEATH
WATER
PERSPECTIVE
!SCRIPTURES
2 SAMUEL 14:14
JOHN 12:24
PSALMS 22:15
1 CORINTHIANS 15:36
