!TITLE
LOOKING FOR A SAFE PLACE?
!WORDS
 After the Persian Gulf War in 1991, a bright yellow ribbon on the 
porch of a Detroit home promised a hero's welcome for a young 
solider. But within a few hours of his homecoming, he had been shot 
to death in the street in front of his own home. National 
sensitivities were shocked. That wasn't the end of the story, 
however.  It was reported that the soldier's widow and her brother 
had been charged with first-degree murder.

   We know that lives will be lost in a war.  And we are not 
surprised by tragedy in crime-ridden neighborhoods.  But we don't 
expect a soldier to survive combat and return home and be shot by his 
own family.

   Just as we expect our homes to be a shelter in a dangerous world, 
so too we expect the church to be a safe place for God's children in 
a troubled world.  There's a special kind of disillusionment that 
occurs when burdened Christians are betrayed by gossip, lies, or 
selfish ambition in the very place where they should find love and 
harmony.
!TOPICS
CHURCH
UNITY, CHRISTIAN
BETRAYAL
GOSSIP
SLANDER
