!TITLE
GOD'S GRACE
!WORDS
   When Twila Paris was 19, she volunteered to take care of her 
younger brother and two younger sisters as well as her sick 
grandmother who lived with them so that her mother could go on a 
ministry trip with her father.  It was only for three weeks and Twila 
was confident that she could handle things.  So her mother went.

   Twila says, "Everything was OK.  Not easy, but OK...  Until one 
night a few days before my parents were due home from their trip.  My 
aunt called to tell me that Mom and Dad had been in a terrible car 
accident in Germany.  They were both critically injured, and Dad 
would be in the hospital for at least two months.  Mom, too--if she 
lived.  She was in a coma, and the doctors didn't expect her to 
survive.

    "People all over the world began to pray for my parents.  I 
didn't know how to tell my sick grandmother that her daughter was 
fighting for her life thousands of miles away.

    "A few nights later, my other grandmother, who lived next door, 
rang the doorbell at 3 a.m. 'Twila, come quickly!  Your grandfather 
is dying!' As I threw on my clothes, my heart pounded wildly. I 
didn't know if I would ever see my parents again.  I was responsible 
for a sick grandmother and three children.  And now this!"

   At the end of her rope, Twila found that that was when God began 
to pour out His grace.  Her grandfather had a heart attack that night 
but he recovered.  In the difficult days that followed, Twila learned 
to walk in supernatural strength. Her mother came out of the coma, 
and both her parents recovered fully from their injuries. God's grace 
was sufficient.
   [Moody, Jan 1993.  Page 30.]
!TOPICS
GRACE, GOD'S
STRENGTH, GOD'S
HARDSHIPS
