!TITLE
BEHIND THE IRON CURTAIN
!WORDS
 Back when Russia and Eastern Europe were under communism, some 
Christians took great risks to get Bibles and Christian books into 
those countries. One missionary told this story:

    "We were transporting a couple of boxes of books to some 
believers--and were about to cross the border.  We had placed our 
cargo in the rear of the vehicle and merely covered it with a 
blanket.  We also had camping equipment and sleeping bags in the 
vehicle.

    "We pulled up to the border and found ourselves at the end of a 
long line.  As soon as we arrived, an official-looking man in plain 
clothes walked along the entire line of cars to us.  He told us to 
park in a nearby inspection area.

    "Then he commanded, 'Empty everything out of the back.'

    "While we obeyed, he waited in the nearby office.  Soon we had 
everything out of the vehicle--except for the boxes of literature 
beneath the blankets.

    "When our inspector returned, he was accompanied by a German 
shepherd dog on a chain. The man pointed to us, and the dog began 
sniffing our legs.  The he pointed to our belongings, and his canine 
partner checked them.

    "The two of them inspected our entire pile of camping equipment, 
food, and supplies.  Then they circled our vehicle with the dog 
sniffing the wheelwells, the front grill, and under the bumper.
    "Next they examined the area around the front seat and under the 
dashboard.  Finally, the pair returned to the rear of the vehicle.

    "I thought to myself, 'If they go inside the back of the vehicle, 
there's no way in the world they'll miss our literature.  Just then 
man and dog discovered our boxes.  The official pointed to them, and 
the dog sniffed carefully.  No reaction.

    "Abruptly he turned and said, 'OK you can go.'

    "Later we learned that the man was a narcotics agent looking for 
drugs--not literature!  The dog wasn't trained to sniff for Bibles, 
and the agent relied on his dog rather than on his own eyes!
    "We could only rejoice at God's protection!"

   [The Persecuted, by Kevin Dyer.  Pages 11-12.]
!TOPICS
PROTECTION, GOD'S
PERSECUTION
