!TITLE
SHARP
!WORDS
 William Ezell tells the story of two lumberjacks, "a younger one and 
an older one, [who] raced to see who could cut down the most trees in 
a single day.  At the end of the day the winner was obvious.  The 
older lumberjack had won.  The younger man could not believe it!

    "'How could you have cut down more trees than I did?' he asked.  
'Every hour you sat down while I kept right on cutting.  I don't 
understand.  How could you have cut more trees while sitting so much?'

    "'When I sat down, I was sharpening my axe,' the older lumberjack 
said.  'Why didn't you stop to sharpen your axe?'

    "'I didn't have time,' the younger man said. 'I was too busy 
cutting.'

    "To be an effective servant, to make my life count for Christ, I 
need to take time regularly to'sharpen' my life."
   [Decision, Jan 1994.  Page 15.]
