!TITLE
AMERICA'S KINDEST CITY
!WORDS
 Byron Paulus writes, "In 1940, a study of 43 American cities ranked 
Rochester, New York, as the'kindest' U.S. city.  Then, in a more 
recent study, conducted between 1990 and 1992, Rochester was once 
again designated as the kindest city. The evaluation was based on a 
series of tests in which researchers pretended to accidentally drop 
something on the street, or to be in need of assistance in some way.  
In both studies, more people went out of their way to be helpful in 
Rochester than in any other city.

    "Impressed by these results, one writer determined to find out 
why Rochester stood out above other cities.  His search led him to 
conclude that the city's history of generosity can be traced back to 
its earliest days, when Charles Finney spent six months preaching and 
conducting prayer meetings in Rochester, in the midst of what we know 
as the Second Great Awakening.  Hundreds of residents were converted 
in those days; those converts renounced their selfish ways and began 
to get involved in various forms of philanthropy and social and moral 
reform.  This writer traced a century and a half track record of 
generosity, kindness, and volunteerism back to its roots in revival!"

   [Revival Report, Oct 1994.  Page 2.]
!TOPICS
KINDNESS
GENEROSITY
REVIVAL
