!TITLE
THE LONELIEST PERSON IN NEW YORK CITY
!WORDS
  "As a couple prayed in their apartment, they were led to pray for 
'the loneliest person in all of New York City.'  Since the United 
States had recently bombed Libya, they prayed for the Libyan 
ambassador to the United Nations.  Getting up from their knees, they 
decided to invite the ambassador to their home for the Thanksgiving 
weekend.  Lo and behold, he agreed to come.

    "They were nervous, never having entertained internationals 
before.  Yet they had a wonderful time together.  Partway into the 
weekend, the ambassador ventured, 'Could I ask you a question? Why 
did you invite me?'  They replied, 'We were praying for the loneliest 
person in Manhattan and you came to mind, and then we decided to 
invite you.'  Nothing more was said about it, and they parted with 
great warmth.

    "A letter of thanks arrived from the ambassador.  Then, to their 
astonishment, they received a letter from Muammar Khadafy thanking 
them for their kindness and inviting them on an all-expense-paid trip 
to Libya as guests of the president. They went and were royally 
received and given an audience with President Khadafy.

    "The president asked why they had invited the ambassador, and 
they told him.  Toward the end of their visit, the American asked if 
he could pray for the president and was given permission to do so.  
When he had finished, the president thanked him with tears in his 
eyes.  He asked if the American would do this again. 'Of course, I 
will, Mr. President,' he replied.  'I'll pray for you every day.'

    "'Oh, no,' said Mr. Khadafy.  'What I mean is, will you do this 
again on national television?' The American then had the opportunity 
to pray in front of cameras that broadcast throughout the nation of 
Libya as he prayed for the salvation of the president and his country.

    "What tremendous opportunities come when we listen to that still 
small voice of the Holy Spirit, nudging us in our prayers to be 
concerned about the lonely, the needy, the lost in our world."

   [From Romancing the Globe by Dan Harrison and Gordon Aeschliman, 
InterVarsity Press, 1993. Quoted in Servant, Nov/Dec 1994.  Page 5.]
!TOPICS
PRAYER, ANSWERED
