!TITLE
HIDDEN TREASURES
!WORDS
 Martin Buber tells the story of a Polish rabbi: "After many years of 
great poverty, which had never undermined his faith in God, Rabbi 
Eisek, son of Rabbi Yekel of Cracow, had a dream one night.  In the 
dream a voice bade him to take a journey to Prague and to look for 
treasure under the bridge which leads to the king's palace. Rabbi 
Eisek did not pay attention to his dream that first night, except to 
note it.  On the second night when he had the exact same dream, he 
began to get more restless.  On the third night when the same voice 
bade him with a sense of urgency to go to Prague and look for the 
treasure beneath the bridge leading to the king's castle, he awoke 
the next morning, put on his walking shoes, and set out on the long 
journey to Prague.

    "When Rabbi Eisek got there, he found that the bridge was guarded 
by day and night. Nevertheless, he went to the bridge every morning 
and kept walking around it until evening. Finally, the captain of the 
guards, who had been watching him, asked him in a kindly way if he 
was looking for something or waiting for somebody. Rabbi Eisek told 
him of the dream which had brought him there from a faraway city.  
The captain laughed and said, `And so to please the dream, you poor 
fellow, you wore out your shoes to come here!  As for having faith in 
dreams, if I had listened to my dreams, I should have had to make a 
trip to Cracow and dig for treasure under the stove in the room of a 
Jew, a Rabbi Eisek, son of Yekel...that was the name, yes, Eisek, son 
of Yekel.  I can just imagine what that would be like, how I should 
have to try every house where half of the Jews are named Eisek and 
the other half Yekel!'  And he laughed again.

    "Rabbi Eisek bowed to the guard, turned in the direction facing 
his house, made his journey home, and dug up the treasure from under 
his own stove." With the money he built a synagogue.
   How many of us have wandered far afield looking for treasure that 
was right under our noses all the time?
   [Pastoral Psychology, Mar 1995.  Page 233.]
!TOPICS
TREASURE
HOME
RICHES
WANDERING
PRIORITIES
DREAMS
