!TITLE
WHERE THE BATTLE LIES
!WORDS
 Miriam Booth, daughter of the founder of the Salvation Army, was a 
brilliant and cultured woman who began her Christian work with great 
promise and unusual success.  Very soon, however, disease brought her 
to the point of death.  A friend told her it seemed a pity that a 
woman of her capabilities should be hindered by sickness from doing 
the Lord's work.  With deep insight and gentle grace, Miriam replied, 
"It's wonderful to do the Lord's work, but it's greater still to do 
the Lord's will!"
   Commenting on John 17:4, blind minister and hymnwriter George 
Matheson said, "Was the work of the Master indeed done?  Was not His 
heaviest task yet to come?  He had not yet met the dread hour of 
death.  Why did He say, then, that His work was done?  It was because 
He knew that when the will is given, the battle is ended!  The cup 
which our Father gives us to drink is a cup of the will.  It is easy 
for the lips to drain it when once the heart has accepted it.  The 
act is easy after the choice."
!TOPICS
OBEDIENCE
CHOICES
DECISION-MAKING
