!TITLE
TWO LITTLE OLD LADIES
!WORDS
  "The Lewis Awakening, also known as the Hebrides Revival, had 
humble beginnings in the Scottish isles.  Two elderly women (one was 
84 years old and blind, the other 82 years old and bent over with 
arthritis) in the village of Barvas on the island of Lewis agreed to 
pray nightly for revival in their community.  Night after night they 
prayed and interceded.  After some time, unknown to them, a group of 
young men began praying on the other end of town.  As the ladies 
prayed, God revealed to them that Duncan Campbell, a minister of the 
Church of Scotland and one-time principal of the Faith Missionary 
Training Home and Bible College and Edinburgh, would come to Barvas 
to lead them. They wrote him, but he cordially declined, saying his 
schedule was too busy.  They responded, `You may say you will not 
come, but God says you are coming!'

    "Some time later, at a British convention the local pastor from 
Barvas suggested that Campbell come for special meetings, and so he 
finally did in December of 1949.  It was then that God's awesome 
power fell on the Hebrides, bringing conviction of sin and revival.  
The power spread from village to village for four years, transforming 
the very life of the community.  It was not unusual for people to be 
sitting in their homes and suddenly be overwhelmed by the Holy 
Spirit. They would fall on their faces in disgust over their sins and 
weep in repentance.  There were times when the revival spirit was so 
powerful that shops would be closed and church services would last 
several hours or even days.  Prayer meetings became the norm in many 
of the communities.

    "From everything we know about the revival--in human terms--the 
whole thing began with two elderly women on their knees before God."

   [Touch the World Through Prayer by Wesley L. Duewel.  Zondervan, 
1986.]
