!TITLE
WHAT KIND OF GOD TO YOU PRAY TO?
!WORDS
 Morris Chapman writes:  "There is a chilling moment in the novel 
Hawaii by James Michener when a group of savages are dancing before 
their gods. One of the savages hold his baby high in the air, and as 
an act of worship to a pagan god, throws it onto a stone altar, 
cracking the child's skull and instantly killing it.  Looking on, the 
savage's wife turns to another woman and says, `My husband is not 
bad.  With a different god, he would be a different man.'

    "We are no different:  Without the Spirit of God working within 
us, we would be savages serving a god of our own making.  As Oswald 
Chambers wrote, `If the Spirit of God has given you a vision of what 
you are apart from the grace of God...you know there is no criminal 
who is half so bad in actuality as you know yourself to be in 
possibility.'

    "Your prayer life often reveals the God you believe in:  If you 
believe in a distant and uncaring God, then you will pray 
accordingly, making the assumption He is not interested in your 
day-to-day problems.  Yet, if you believe in a God who knows even 
when a sparrow falls to the ground, then you will approach the throne 
of grace boldly, telling God your every need."

   [SBC Life, Oct 1995.  Page 7.]
!TOPICS
LOVE, GOD'S
PRAYER
