!TITLE
GOD AT WORK
!WORDS
"To read of her beginnings, Helena, the mother of Constantine (the 
first Roman emperor to convert to Christianity) seemed to have 
promise of only a depressing, unfulfilling life.  She was the 
daughter of an innkeeper on the Turkish coast, a lowly background of 
her time, and became one of Roman Emperor Constantius I's military 
conquests. For 19 years she was his concubine until banished so 
Constantius I could marry another woman and consolidate his power.

   "But her legacy is extraordinary:  She taught her son about Jesus, 
whom she is said always to have adored.  And she has been described 
as such a devout servant of God that in 324, when she was nearly 70, 
Helena made one of the first pilgrimages to the Holy Land.  Her 
purpose was to establish the importance of Christianity in her 
kingdom and back up her son's Edict of Milan, which ended the 
persecution of Christians.

   "Helena marshalled her experts to search for the true cross in 
Jerusalem's neglected rubble, and they believed they had found the 
location where today thousands come each year to reflect on Christ.  
But beyond her search for any part of Jesus Christ, Helena encouraged 
her son to build churches, appoint Christians to high government 
posts, and adopt a Christian calendar.  While Constantine was not 
entirely successful in turning the Roman Empire toward 
Christianity--and, indeed, some of his theological stances have never 
been resolved--his mother's legacy has survived intact.

   "As writer Evelyn Waugh said, `Helena was a lonely, resolute woman 
with a single concrete, practical task clear before her--to turn eyes 
of the world back to the planks of wood on which their salvation 
hung.'"
   [Virtue, Mar/Apr 1996.  Page 47.]
