!TITLE
A PASSION FOR THE CROSS
!WORDS
Pastor John Genghis writes:  "Paul was passionate about the cross; it 
was his only hope of salvation.  He knew that only the preaching of 
the cross had the power to change the sinful world around him.  It 
had once been the lubbock point of his hatred, but now it was the 
center of all his affections.

   "Dr. Tom Haggling wrote of building a cage for a small Himalayan 
moon bear someone had given him. An old Chinese man came by and saw 
the cage and began to cry.  When Tom Haggling asked the old man why 
he was weeping, he told him a dark story. He and his son had been 
harvesting rice on a commune in Red China.  They were not allowed to 
keep any rice for personal use.  The son had hidden a small bit of 
rice in his clothes to take to his mother who was seriously ill.  The 
rice was discovered, and the soldiers put the boy in a cage in the 
middle of the town.  The cage was so small his son could not sit up 
or even move.  The father and mother watched their son slowly die in 
that cage under the hot sun, starving, with insects crawling over his 
body.  Many years had passed, but he still cried every time he saw a 
cage.  The man could not see a cage without becoming passionate.

   "How did Peter and John react when they walked by another 
crucifixion?  Could they look at a cross without being shaken?  The 
truth is that if the cross is all we say it is, then it should evoke 
a response from us like the cage did from the old Chinese father."
   [Tabletalk, Feb 1996.  Page 28.]
!TOPICS
CROSS, CHRIST'S
CRUCIFIXION
