!TITLE
SIGNS OF REVIVAL
!WORDS
Recently the pastor of a large church in Portland, Oregon, attended a 
weekend prayer retreat with 45 other pastors from that area.  This is 
what he experienced:  "As he sits in the evening communion service, 
he is privately skeptical about what could really happen among a 
group of pastors from different denominations.  As a Pentecostal, he 
is aware of the lingering animosity between his denomination and some 
of the area's Conservative Baptists.

   "After communion, a fellow pastor he does not know addresses the 
group:  `I want to confess tonight that I stand here as a part of the 
Conservative Baptists, and I ask forgiveness of my Pentecostal 
brothers who are here.  I feel we've done more than any other group 
in the city to quench the Spirit of God.  If there is a Pentecostal 
brother willing to stand here at the communion table with me, I'd 
count it a privilege.'

   "Moments later, the Baptist pastor is joined at the communion 
table by a Pentecostal pastor.  This man, whom he had never met, says 
with humility, `Not only do I accept that apology, I want to offer an 
apology on behalf of the Pentecostal church for the arrogance and 
pride that somehow projects an attitude of superiority.'  Through the 
event, the two men become close friends and agree to pray together 
every Wednesday morning."

   [National & International Religion Report, Dec 25, 1995.  Special 
Supplement, Page 1.]
