!TITLE
GO WITH THE FLOW
!WORDS
 Speaker and author Bill Butterworth says that he was something of a 
delinquent when he was in eighth grade.  In metal shop that year, he 
waited until the last day of class to start a project even though he 
knew that his whole grade would depend on how well it turned out.

   The simplest project he could come up with was a screwdriver.  He 
heated a steel rod, put it on the anvil, and smacked the red-hot 
metal with a mallet.  He hit it too hard, however, and flattened it 
more than he was supposed to.  There wasn't time to start over so he 
had to turn it in like it was.  He thought it was the ugliest 
screwdriver he'd ever seen and figured he would flunk the course.

   The next day the shop teacher called Billy up to the front of the 
class and began to make a speech that Billy thought was meant to be 
sarcastic until he said, "Congratulations, Mr. Butterworth, you have 
won the Outstanding Metal Shop Project of the Year Award for 
your...chisel!" Without missing a beat, Bill launched into a little 
acceptance speech in which he thanked all the guys in the class, 
etc.  When somebody said, "I thought it was a screwdriver," Bill 
quickly said, "No, no, I'm sorry, we don't have time for any 
comments.  Thank you very much."

   Reflecting on the experience years later, Bill asks why God would 
allow things to turn out that way.  He concludes, "God was teaching 
me the importance of learning to go with the flow.  I find that the 
more I accept what is happening and try to learn from it, the more 
progress I make."

   [Servant, Fall 1996.  Pages 10-11.]
!TOPICS
WORRY
ANXIETY
GRACE
PROCRASTINATION
IRRESPONSIBILITY
TEENAGERS
