!TITLE
HE HAD IT ALL
!WORDS
 Pastor Bill Hybels tells the story of a man who had spent so much 
time building his business that his wife had finally decided to 
divorce him.  His health was faltering as well.  In desperation he 
sold his company and bought a small marina on a beautiful lake.  His 
wife and children were delighted at the prospect of working together 
in a slow-paced family business.

   The problem was that a change of location didn't change the man's 
approach to life.  He still had this tremendous need to prove 
himself. It took him less than five years to turn that run- down 
little marina into a multimillion-dollar operation.  A friend said to 
him, "You must be very proud of this marina."  His reply was bitter: 
"No, every time I look at it, I feel sick at my stomach.  This 
business has cost me everything."

   During those five years, his wife gave up hope that he would ever 
change and left him.  His kids eventually went their own way.  His 
overextended schedule kept him from being involved in church or any 
spiritual pursuits.  And the stress of running the business had 
worsened his heart condition.  He had wanted to break out of the 
cycle of overwork, but because of his insecurity he fell into the 
trap of making all the same mistakes over again.

   [Honest to God by Bill Hybels.  Zondervan, 1990.  Page 149.]
