!TITLE
WHY ME, LORD?
!WORDS
 Barbara Johnson tells the story of a man who always used to take the 
subway home from work. One day the subway car was especially crowded. 
Now this fellow had a problem with motion sickness from time to time, 
and on this particular afternoon he had overeaten at lunch and had 
been battling an upset stomach ever since.  When he got on the 
subway, he was the last person that could squeeze in before the doors 
closed.

   So there he was with his face practically pressed against the 
window with lighted signs flashing past his nose at 90 miles an 
hour--or so it seemed.  The train swayed and wobbled as it sped 
along, and our friend got sicker and sicker.

   Finally, the subway came to a station, but it wasn't the sick 
man's stop.  As the train screeched to a halt, there were lots of 
people standing on the platform waiting to get on.  As the doors slid 
open, the man suddenly lost his lunch--all over the guy standing 
right in front of him on the platform.

   The poor victim was so stunned he just stood there.  The people 
around him turned their heads, and before anyone could move, the 
subway doors slid shut, and the train roared away, leaving the 
unfortunate man standing there with somebody else's lunch all over 
his three-piece suit.  He turns to the man behind him and says, "Why 
ME?"

   Barbara Johnson comments, "This is the perfect illustration of the 
WRONG attitude for responding to life's trials."

   [I'm So Glad You Told Me What I Didn't Wanna Hear by Barbara 
Johnson.  Word, 1996.  Page 94.]
