!TITLE
GET READY TO BE AMBUSHED!
!WORDS
 John Wesley Powell had only one arm.  He was wounded in the Civil 
War and had his arm amputated, but he didn't let that slow him down. 
Powell had a dream.  He wanted to take an expedition down the 
Colorado River all the way through the Grand Canyon.  In those days, 
it was commonly believed that it couldn't be done.  One explorer even 
said it would NEVER be done--ever! These skeptics certainly had 
plenty of evidence on their side.  Several expeditions had tried, but 
not one of them had survived.  No wonder people thought Powell was 
insane.

   Still, the one-armed explorer thought he could do it. So on May 
24, 1869, Powell and nine other men got into their four small boats 
and set off on their thousand-mile journey.  They faced numerous 
hazards along the way:  killer rapids by the hundreds, waterfalls, 
boulders the size of houses, and the loss of boats, food supplies, 
and instruments.

   But 100 days later, two boats appeared carrying Powell and five 
men.  People had given them up for lost weeks before.  They had 
practically starved and exposure had taken its toll, but they had 
made it through!  What about the others?  One had gotten cold feet 
right away and turned back after only a few days.  The three others, 
who had had a hard time getting along with Powell, left the party and 
climbed out of the canyon but were ambushed by Indians and killed.

   When John Wesley Powell got into the boat to begin this trek down 
the Colorado, he knew it would be no pleasure cruise.  He expected to 
encounter problems.  It's the same with us--we've got to anticipate 
the ambushes we're likely to encounter.

   [Finishing Strong by Steve Farrar.  Multnomah, 1995.  Pages 23-28.]
!TOPICS
PREPARATION
ALERTNESS
PERSEVERANCE
DETERMINATION
VISION
OBSTACLES
