!TITLE
THE VALUE OF KNOWLEDGE
!WORDS
 The story is told of Christopher Columbus that he once was stranded 
in Jamaica.  The native people refused to give him the supplies he 
needed, so he resorted to a ruse.  Knowing that an eclipse of the 
moon would take place the next evening, he told the chief, "The God I 
serve is very powerful. If you don't give me the goods I require 
today, tomorrow night He will punish you and the moon will lose its 
light!"  The chief still refused, but the next night when the shadow 
began to creep across the face of the moon, he changed his mind 
quickly.  Columbus got what he needed.

   An Englishman traveling in the Sudan in the early 1900s found 
himself in similar circumstances.  "If you don't do as I say," he 
warned the tribal leaders sternly, "vengeance will fall upon you, and 
tonight the moon will refuse to shine."  The tall chieftain looked at 
him bewildered for a moment and then his face brightened and he said, 
"Oh, if you mean the lunar eclipse, that's not until tomorrow night."
   [Adapted from The Executive Speechwriter Newsletter.  
802-748-4472.]
!TOPICS
KNOWLEDGE
TRUTH
