!TITLE
WHOLEHEARTED DEVOTION
!WORDS
 Saint Anthony, born in 251 A.D. in Egpyt, was not the first ascetic, 
but he was the first monk to leave the city to try to find God in the 
desert. At that time many Christians were leaving the ordinary 
pursuits of life in order to focus on devoting themselves completely 
to God.

   When Anthony was 20, his parents died.  He inherited their estate 
and also became responsible for his younger sister.  Sitting in 
church a few months later, Anthony heard something that changed his 
life.  It was what Jesus said to the rich young ruler:  "If you want 
to be perfect, go sell your possessions and give to the poor...  Then 
come, follow me."  He took it as an invitation from God Himself.  
Right away he sold off his parent's estate and gave the proceeds to 
the poor, keeping only enough to provide for his sister.

   Out in the desert, Anthony developed a lifestyle that he followed 
for 85 years.  He fasted until after sunset each day.  Then all he 
would eat was six ounces of bread soaked in water, occasionally 
seasoned with a little salt.  When he got older, he would allow 
himself a few dates and a little oil now and then.  He had a small 
garden in which he raised wheat for his bread and vegetables to offer 
his visitors.  His work was weaving mats out of palm leaves.

   He spent his days and nights in constant prayer.  He especially 
enjoyed praying at night and sometimes complained that the sunrise 
took away the light of inner contemplation.

   In spite of his austere diet and lifestyle, he remained strong and 
healthy even in old age.
   [Miracles of the Saints by Bert Ghezzi. Zondervan, 1996.]
!TOPICS
DISCIPLINES, SPIRITUAL
FASTING
