!TITLE
LOOKING AHEAD
!WORDS
 When he was a boy, Howard Hendricks liked to wander over to a park 
near his house and watch the older men play checkers.  One day one of 
the men asked him if he wanted to play.  The boy said, "Sure."

   They started the game.  At first it seemed easy.  He jumped one 
after another of the man's checkers.  Then all at once the man took 
one of his checkers and hopped and skipped all the way across the 
board and hollered, "King me, boy!" Then he proceeded to eliminate 
Howard's pieces one by one with that king.

   Says Hendricks, "That day I learned something about long-range 
vision.  No ones minds losing a few checkers if he's headed for king 
territory. Only with God's long-range perspective will we steer 
toward ultimate victory."

   [Moody, Nov/Dec 1996.  Page 42.]
