!TITLE
NO MATTER WHAT ELSE CHANGES
!WORDS
It was a tragedy.  Roy and Karen Pike of Columbus, Ohio, had gone to 
Williamsburg, Virginia, to celebrate their 25th anniversary.  Their 
car ran into an 18-wheeler parked by the side of the of highway, and 
the couple was killed instantly. Back home, their three sons, aged 
20, 17, and 16, had to open anniversary cards and sympathy cards the 
same day.  Flowers sent for celebration were used in the funeral 
instead.

   These three boys took on the duties of manhood, selecting caskets 
and cemetery plots for their parents.  After handling all the funeral 
arrangements, 17-year-old Timothy Pike testified to their pastor 
about how God was showing His faithfulness in the midst of tragic 
circumstances. "Right now," he said, "I see God as my shelf. 
Everything on it has been moved around, changed, or broken.  I know 
that things are always going to be different, changing (more now than 
ever before) but the shelf that I can put everything on hasn't 
changed.  God is still the same."

   As the pastor told the packed church that day at the funeral, "God 
is indeed our shelf.  No matter how rearranged the things on that 
shelf become, God will always sustain us."
   [Homiletics, Apr-Jun 1991.  Page 6.]
