!TITLE
CHRISTIAN PRINCIPLES
!WORDS
Albert Camus, the famous French writer, was an atheist and often 
criticized Christianity, but Harold O. J. Brown says, "his attacks 
smack more of disappointment with the hypocrisy and pusilanimity of 
Christians, rather than the faith itself. Although he did not accept 
its doctrines, Camus attacked the church not because its faith was 
wrong, but because so many of its representatives failed to meet even 
the requirements that could be placed on them by simple humanity, 
such as opposing murder, torture, and cruelty, and seeking justice, 
including economic justice.  Much of his writing suggests that his 
problem with Christianity was not that he could not believe it, but 
that he could not believe those who professed it.

   "He insisted that Christians have a duty to stand up for their 
convictions and to wage war against all manner of evils and 
excesses.  Camus explained that he demanded this of them not as 
though he were a Christian, but as a human being of his fellow 
humans.  One has the feeling that he expected Christians to be better 
than run of the mill humans but found them as vacillating and 
cowardly as the rest, if not necessarily worse."

   [Religion & Society Report, May 1997.  Page 3.]
