!TITLE
A REAL TRAGEDY
!WORDS
In the movie Field of Dreams there is a scene where Ray Kinsella is 
talking with an old man named Moonlight Graham, who had at one time 
been on a major league baseball team.  His career on the field, 
however, was almost incredibly short. He only got to play in one 
game, and then it was for only a few short minutes.  He never even 
got up to bat.

   That had been many years before, and Graham was an old man now.  
He had become a doctor and given his life to alleviating the 
sufferings of others. Kinsella keeps thinking about how disappointed 
Graham must have been.  He says, "For five minutes, you were that 
close to your dream.  It would kill some men to be that close to 
their dream and not touch it. They would consider it a tragedy."

   Graham just smiles and looks him in the eye and says, "Son, if I'd 
only been a doctor for five minutes, now THAT would have been a real 
tragedy."

   [The Worth of a Man by Dave Dravecky. Zondervan, 1996.  Page 23.]
