!TITLE
WHY DO WE REMAIN SILENT?
!WORDS
After denying it for decades, the Red Cross finally admitted in the 
spring of 1997 that it had not been completely honest about how it 
had responded to the Holocaust. Thousands of documents had been 
hidden from the public until recently. There are several parallels 
between that story and the role of the church in spreading the gospel 
of Christ.

   Members of the International Committee of the Red Cross were the 
only outsiders allowed into Nazi concentration camps before Germany 
surrendered in 1945. For half a century, the Committee was criticized 
for not doing more to alleviate the suffering it found. After the 
Committee gave nearly 60,000 pages of records to the U.S. Holocaust 
Memorial Museum in Washington, D.C., the real story came out.

   The documents revealed how many people, governments, and 
organizations failed in their human responsibility. Alan Kraut, a 
history professor and Holocaust expert at American University in 
Washington, said, "What we can say is that the Red Cross knew and 
didn't raise its voice." What do we know as Christians?  And do we 
raise our voices enough?

   Miles Lerman, chairman of the U.S. Holocaust Council, said: 
"People, good people, decided to look the other way, including people 
in the Red Cross. I wouldn't describe them as villains, but as part 
of the world that found it more convenient to remain silent."  How 
many of us find it "more convenient to remain silent" when it comes 
to sharing the message of salvation?

   In 1944 Red Cross delegates visited a camp called Terezin, in the 
former Czechoslovakia. They reported that the camp appeared 
"unthreatening." The camp had a symphony orchestra and a "warm" cafe. 
When the delegates arrived, they were greeted by one prisoner dressed 
in a black suit and top hat. About 40 children performed a short 
opera. Survivors say that soon after the Red Cross delegation left, 
many of those children were killed by the Nazis. Just as the Nazis 
used the Red Cross to deceive the rest of the world into thinking 
that things were not really as bad as they thought--that there was 
really no need for action on their part--Satan often deceives us into 
thinking that evangelizing the world for Christ is really not that 
urgent a matter.

   The documents released indicate many reasons why the Red Cross 
failed to act. Among them was that the organization was confused 
about its role and responsibilities. Isn't it the same with churches 
and Christian organizations today? They are not reaching people for 
Christ and have no burden for others because they have no vision, no 
understanding of their role and responsibilities, no comprehension of 
what the Scriptures teach regarding the purpose of the church in the 
world.

   [The Timothy Report, Swan Lake Communications, Sep 29, 1997.]
!TOPICS
EVANGELISM
