!TITLE
CHANGING HORSES MIDSTREAM
!WORDS
  A man named Alfred was shocked while reading the newspaper one 
morning to come across his own obituary.  It was just a mistake, of 
course, but it really shook Alfred up. He began to reevaluate the 
course of his life.  He had devoted his efforts--very successfully, 
by the way--to the development of dynamite.
   That day, reading his own death notice, he realized that he didn't 
want to be remembered for giving the world the ability to blow itself 
up. How much better, he thought, to do something of lasting value in 
the areas of peace, culture, and science.
   He gave it a lot of thought and came up with a way to do that: 
using his wealth to fund a program that would honor the outstanding 
achievements of people in those fields.  In case you haven't guessed, 
Alfred's last name was Nobel, and the program he set up is the Nobel 
Prizes.
   What are you doing with your life today?  Is that what you want to 
be remembered for?  Later in his life Alfred Nobel said, "Every man 
ought to have the right to prepare a new epitaph midstream in his 
life."
   [Finish Strong by Richard G. Capen. HarperSanFrancisco, 1996.  
Pages 124-125.]
