!TITLE
FOCUS ON HIS FACE
!WORDS
Max Lucado tells the story of being caught in a storm with his 
father.  They were out fishing when the weather turned nasty all of a 
sudden.  It was not a large boat, and to nine-year-old Max the waves 
appeared huge.  Thunder rumbled and lightning flashed across the 
sky.  They couldn't see the shore through the rain and fog.  Max was 
beginning to wonder if they would make it back.

   He sat in the front of the boat looking back toward his father, 
who was sitting in the stern with his hand on the throttle.  He had 
headed the small craft toward the nearest beach, and they were making 
some progress, but the waves were getting bigger.

   Max looked for the sun, but it was hidden by the clouds.  He 
squinted through the rain, trying to make out the trees along the 
shore, but he couldn't see them.  All he could see was waves. The 
only reassuring sight was his father's face, as he peered into the 
storm with his jaw set, grimacing.  Water dripped off his baseball 
cap; his shirt was soaked and sticking to his skin.

   At that moment Max decided to quit looking at the storm and look 
only at his dad.  Looking at the lake brought fear; watching his 
father brought peace.  He focused so intently on his dad that day 
that 30 years later he still has a clear mental picture of that calm 
face.

   Max says, "God wants us to do the same.  He wants us to focus our 
eyes on Him.  What good does it do to focus on the storm?"

    [He Still Moves Stones by Max Lucado.  Word, 1993.  Pages 
158-159.]
!TOPICS
