!TITLE
SEEING DIFFERENTLY
!WORDS
Lyn Johnston draws a comic strip called "For Better or For Worse."  
In one strip, we see a little girl sitting near a window watching the 
afternoon sunshine.  She says to her mother, "Look, there's a sunbeam 
coming in through the window. Doesn't it look like something you can 
touch?  I'm pretending it's a piece of fabric that angels clothes are 
made of.  Now I'm pretending it's a magic slide.  Now I'm pretending 
it's a movie projector."  She looks at her mother and says pensively, 
"You can see neat things in a sunbeam, can't you, Mom?"  Her mother 
nods and says, "Uh-huh," but she's thinking to herself:  "A few 
minutes ago all I saw was dust."

   We need to see differently, to see more than dust, to see Christ 
breaking into our lives in unexpected places and ways.  He can shine 
even through the most mundane aspects of our lives.

   [Christian Ministry, Mar/Apr 1998.  Page 26.]
!TOPICS
