!TITLE
ROBBING YOURSELF
!WORDS
In the 1920s there was a very successful man named Arthur Berry.  He 
often visited the homes of the wealthy elite of Boston, but he did it 
when no one was at home.  Mr. Berry was a jewel thief.  It got so 
that his visits became a sort of status symbol among the upper-class 
ladies around town.

   But during one of his nocturnal visitations, the police caught up 
with Berry and shot him.  He was wounded by three bullets and fell 
through a window.  As he lay there on the ground with pieces of 
shattered glass piercing his body, he said through the pain, "I ain't 
gonna do this any more."

   Arthur Berry spent 20 years behind bars.  After his release he 
took up residence in a quiet New England town and led the life of a 
respectable citizen.  Eventually when word got out that the famous 
jewel thief was living in this small New England town, reporters 
converged on his house seeking interviews.  One reporter came up with 
this question:  "Mr. Berry, you stole from a lot of different rich 
people, but who did you steal the most from?"

   Berry didn't even have to stop and think about his answer.  He 
said, "That's the easiest question I have ever been asked.  The 
individual from who I stole the most was a man named Arthur Berry.  I 
could have done anything, been an executive on Wall Street, a 
successful businessman, or anything I wanted to be, but I took my 
God-given talents and developed them illegitimately.  I could have 
made it big in business, but I spent two-thirds of my life behind 
bars."

   [The Preacher's Magazine, Sep-Nov 1997.  Page 51.]
!TOPICS
MORALS
STEALING
DECISION-MAKING
WASTING TIME
PURPOSE
REGRET
!SCRIPTURES
