!TITLE
STAY WITH IT
!WORDS
Mark Twain liked to tell the story about an old man who had been a 
riverboat pilot on the Mississippi River.  As a reporter for a St. 
Louis newspaper, Twain had been sent to interview the retired 
riverman on the occasion of his 100th birthday. Naturally, one of the 
questions in the interview was about what the man attributed his 
longevity to.  He gave the expected answer concerning avoiding bad 
habits and cultivating good ones, but Twain wasn't satisfied with 
that.

   He challenged the old man, saying that he knew a man who had 
followed that advice but only lived to be 80.  He asked the former 
pilot how he could account for that.  Not intimidated in the least, 
the centenarian answered calmly, "Well, he just didn't keep it up 
long enough."

   [The Speaker's Book of Illustrations by Herbert Prochnow.  Baker, 
1960.  Page 45.]
